      <td colspan="3"><p><span class="style1"><br>        
        Before you begin reading, get the Orientation Binder and Safety Orientation video from the office.</span><span class="style1"><br>
        <br>
        </span></p>
      </td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td colspan="2"><p align="left"><span class="style1"> Despite a 40% drop between 1992 and 2003, foodservice still leads the United States in workplace injuries. The vast majority of accidents and injuries occur in the food preparation areas. The most common mishaps are slips, trips, falls, repetitive-stress damage and lacerations. This statistic is also true for our company. </span></p></td>
      <td><div align="center"><img src="../../../images/cast.gif" width="118" height="185"></div></td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td colspan="3"><p align="left" class="style1">Typically, the safety program is a low priority in most restaurants. While some elements of a safety program are mandated by the government, most managers are satisfied to do the minimum, giving them more time for other things that they deem more important. However, a well managed safety program can generate huge savings.</p>
          <div align="left">
            <ul>
              <li class="style1">reduction of injuries = less turnover, less time loss days, happier employees</li>
              <li class="style1">fewer injuries - lower Workers' Compensation expenses and lower insurance premiums</li>
              <li><span class="style1">insurance premiums are based on the number of accidents per year and their severity. So, one bad year can have an affect on your insurance costs for the next three years! </span></li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <p align="left"><span class="style1">Our company has realized a safe working environment is crucial and has developed a comprehensive safety program to promote the well-being of our employees and save cost to our stores. This programs includes:</span></p>
          <div align="left">
            <ul>
              <li class="style1">A complete Safety Orientation for each new employee</li>
              <li class="style1">An functional store Safety Committee</li>
              <li class="style1">Ongoing employee safety training</li>
              <li class="style1">Regular safety inspections</li>
              <li class="style1">A Safety and Security Audit </li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <p align="left"><span class="style1">As part of our reading assignments and activities over the next few days we will be exploring Shari's complete safety program beginning with the Safety Orientation.</span></p>
          <p align="left">&nbsp;</p></td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><div align="center"><img src="../../../images/opps.gif" width="129" height="129"></div></td>
      <td colspan="2"><div align="left">
          <p class="style1"><u>Shari's Safety Orientation</u></p>
          <p class="style1">In order to communicate our safety requirements each new employee is required to receive a Safety Orientation along with the new employee orientation. During the Safety Orientation you will be teaching our safety program and responsibilities to the new employees. You will be explaining and demonstrating the proper use of equipment, the safe use of chemicals and proper lifting to name a few. The benefits of teaching new employees correct safety procedures before they start training are fewer accidents and increased safety awareness. <br>
              <br>
          </p>
      </div></td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td colspan="2"><p align="left" class="style1">Prior to conducting a Safety Orientation you need to gather the following items:</p>
          <div align="left">
            <ul>
              <li><span class="style1">TV/VCR</span></li>
              <li><span class="style1">Safety Orientation Video</span></li>
              <li><span class="style1">Lifting Safely Video</span></li>
              <li><span class="style1">Is it Worth Your Life (Robbery Video)</span></li>
              <li><span class="style1">MSDS Binder</span></li>
              <li><span class="style1">Orientation Booklet</span></li>
              <li><span class="style1">Emergency Situations Binder</span></li>
              <li><span class="style1">Food Safety Training Workbook</span></li>
              <li><span class="style1">Food Safety Training Booklet</span></li>
              <li><span class="style1">Employee Orientation Binder - Tab: Safety Orientation Manager's Outline </span></li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <ul>
        </ul></td>
      <td><p>&nbsp;</p>
          <p>&nbsp;</p>
          <p>&nbsp;</p>
          <p><img src="../../../images/icons/orient_binder_replay.gif" width="240" height="192"></p></td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td colspan="3"><div align="left">
          <p class="style1">In order to impress upon the new employee the importance of their Safety Orientation you must be organized, prepared and know the information you will be covering. Gather all needed items <u><strong>before</strong></u> the new employee arrives for orientation and prepare the area you will use. </p>
          <p class="style1">If you haven't already, print of the <a href="safety_orientation_checklist.htm" target="_blank">Safety Orientation Checklist</a> and get the Orientation Binder and Safety Orientation video from the office. Find the Safety Orientation Manager's Outline tab in the Employee Orientation Binder - this is a script that you will use during the orientation. This script follows the video and the safety orientation checklist and is designed to use in conjunction with the video and the checklist. Using these three aids together helps us conduct a very thorough orientation that is consistent from employee to employee. It also ensures that we meet the legal training requirements outlined by OSHA and WISHA: the federal and state safety and health association. </p>
          <p class="style1">For example:</p>
          <p class="style1"><u>#1 from the Manager's Outline</u> tells you what to say to the new employee to introduce the Safety Orientation: &quot;Every new employee will receive a Safety Orientation. We will cover employee responsibilities, use of chemicals and first aid procedures for each, MSDS binder, equipment safety, disease prevention, lifting procedures, protective equipment, reporting of accidents and unsafe conditions, Safety Committee, and complete a safety tour of the restaurant.&quot; It then instructs you to show the Safety Orientation Video.</p>
          <p class="style1"><u>#1 from the Employee Safety Orientation Checklist</u> is: Employee Safety Orientation video Presentation and Review Safety Orientation Introduction.</p>
          <p class="style1">At the beginning of the orientation, instruct the new employee to initial each section of the Safety Orientation Checklist as it is covered. Their initials will prove that each section was covered with them, whereas a check mark could have been made by anyone. When an OSHA or WISHA inspector come in, one of the thing he will ask for is proof of safety training - the checklist complete with the employee's initials and signature will satisfy this request. </p>
          <p class="style1">While viewing the Safety Video you will need to stay with the employee and watch the video with them. During the video it will instruct you to &quot;stop the video now&quot; and explain or demonstrate items such as; emergency reference binder, proper hand washing, proper lifting and explaining the MSDS binder.</p>
          <p class="style1">During the safety orientation both you and the new employee will have forms to sign. Remember, these are legal documents that provide proof of training - they are important. All of these form are located in the Company and Safety Orientation booklet that the employee receives. Review the following list of items requiring signatures.<br>
            <br> 
          </p>
